WEBVTT
Kind: captions
Language: en

00:00:04.089 --> 00:00:07.169
&gt;&gt;Chade-Meng Tan: Good afternoon, everybody.

00:00:07.169 --> 00:00:13.190
So have you ever had the experience of making
friends with somebody and then later discover

00:00:13.190 --> 00:00:16.180
that he's a famous rock star? [laughs]

00:00:16.180 --> 00:00:17.180
[laughter]

00:00:17.180 --> 00:00:21.340
So I had that experience with our honored
guest today, Salman Ahmad.

00:00:21.340 --> 00:00:27.021
I met him at a United Nations and I was impressed
with his talents, his personal kindness, and

00:00:27.021 --> 00:00:32.369
his compassion. And so we sort of became like
instant friends.

00:00:32.369 --> 00:00:39.730
And then I discovered that he's a famous rock
star. It's like a member of the biggest band

00:00:39.730 --> 00:00:47.690
and long lasting rock back in South Asia called
Junoon and he's a national Pakistani icon.

00:00:47.690 --> 00:00:55.350
And beyond being a rock star, Salman is also
an eminent humanitarian. He's a United Nations

00:00:55.350 --> 00:01:02.360
Google ambassador. He played the first ever
rock concert in war torn Kashmir, and he's

00:01:02.360 --> 00:01:08.310
the first Pakistani musician ever to perform
at a Nobel Peace Prize ceremony.

00:01:08.310 --> 00:01:17.509
He is also helping to bring peace between
Pakistan and India and he's working to help

00:01:17.509 --> 00:01:23.279
Pakistan's three million displaced people.
Such an amazing human being.

00:01:23.279 --> 00:01:28.740
And my friends, please give a warm welcome
to my friend, Salman Ahmad.

00:01:28.740 --> 00:01:31.439
[applause]

00:01:31.439 --> 00:01:36.991
&gt;&gt;Salman Ahmad: Thank you.

00:01:36.991 --> 00:01:37.991
&gt;&gt;Chade-Meng Tan: Thank you.

00:01:37.991 --> 00:01:38.991
&gt;&gt;Salman Ahmad: Thanks for having me. Thank
you.

00:01:38.991 --> 00:01:39.991
[sound of ticking]

00:01:39.991 --> 00:01:40.991
Thank you and peace be upon you.

00:01:40.991 --> 00:01:47.770
I've heard my friend Meng saying that the
culture here is of the "yes" culture, and

00:01:47.770 --> 00:01:54.590
we don't ask for permission but we ask for
forgiveness. So I shall begin this talk with

00:01:54.590 --> 00:01:55.620
asking your forgiveness as well.

00:01:55.620 --> 00:01:59.759
[pause]

00:01:59.759 --> 00:02:12.069
This is a time, 2011, the world is in flux;
cultures are in flux; there's a collision

00:02:12.069 --> 00:02:20.260
of cultures happening and I find myself as
an artist born in Lahore Pakistan. Anybody

00:02:20.260 --> 00:02:22.459
from Pakistan out there?

00:02:22.459 --> 00:02:23.459
[pause]

00:02:23.459 --> 00:02:26.520
So for anybody from India out there?

00:02:26.520 --> 00:02:35.819
So as you know you guys are all at Google,
but most of the career choices you get growing

00:02:35.819 --> 00:02:43.709
up in Pakistan or India, like the ones I got,
were two choices: doctor and doctor.

00:02:43.709 --> 00:02:44.819
[laughter]

00:02:44.819 --> 00:02:52.159
And that was drummed into me even before I
could learn how to say, "Mama" or "Papa."

00:02:52.159 --> 00:02:53.390
Ami, Abba.

00:02:53.390 --> 00:03:01.469
And so my life has been, growing in a culture
with certain do's and don'ts but thinking

00:03:01.469 --> 00:03:03.180
completely out of the box.

00:03:03.180 --> 00:03:11.879
My earliest memory, when I was growing up
we used to have family weddings in the backyard;

00:03:11.879 --> 00:03:17.730
no five star hotels, no community centers,
backyards. And at our family weddings there

00:03:17.730 --> 00:03:23.019
used to be Qawwali music. Anybody heard of
Qawwali music out there?

00:03:23.019 --> 00:03:32.650
So my earliest memory was at a wedding where
I see two rows of musicians, a front row of

00:03:32.650 --> 00:03:38.689
lead singers with harmoniums, and a back row
of Tabla players and hand clappers; strong

00:03:38.689 --> 00:03:40.459
hand clappers.

00:03:40.459 --> 00:03:47.930
And I was maybe six, seven years old but what
struck me was that the melody and the rhythm

00:03:47.930 --> 00:03:54.230
it did something to my heart; went through
my ears and it connected with me, the vibrations

00:03:54.230 --> 00:03:59.379
connected with me in such a way that it created
curiosity.

00:03:59.379 --> 00:04:01.299
[pause]

00:04:01.299 --> 00:04:02.560
What is that? What is that?

00:04:02.560 --> 00:04:10.680
And one of the earliest melodies is of a poet
from South Asia, a renaissance man from the

00:04:10.680 --> 00:04:18.120
12th century -- his name was Amir Khusro and
Hazat Amir Khusrau, created, was the father

00:04:18.120 --> 00:04:26.030
of Qawwali music. And his sole reason for
listening to a lot of Bhajan music which was

00:04:26.030 --> 00:04:30.580
around at that time, I mean that's what he
grew up with was listening to Hindu devotional

00:04:30.580 --> 00:04:37.880
music, the Bhajan music. His mother was Indian,
his father was Persian, so he had a lot of

00:04:37.880 --> 00:04:49.740
diverse cultural influences: Arabic folk poems,
Persian melodies and he fused Bhajan, Arabic

00:04:49.740 --> 00:04:55.040
folk music, Persian poetry, and out of that
came Qawwali.

00:04:55.040 --> 00:05:03.360
But although he was using existing building
blocks off elements that which were already

00:05:03.360 --> 00:05:08.509
around, he came up with something completely
new and which took over the subcontinent.

00:05:08.509 --> 00:05:15.069
As you know, the region which is now India,
Bangladesh, and Pakistan, Afghanistan very

00:05:15.069 --> 00:05:21.240
diverse, so many different languages, so many
different faith traditions, ethnicities, yet

00:05:21.240 --> 00:05:27.600
through music, the communication of music
he was able to bring Hindus and Muslims and

00:05:27.600 --> 00:05:35.280
people from other,-- later on in the Sikh
tradition as well together in unity.

00:05:35.280 --> 00:05:40.460
And the concept of unity was the reason. I
mean he didn't wanna be number one on MTV,

00:05:40.460 --> 00:05:47.190
he didn't wanna be Facebooked or Twittered,
he was just making this music 'cause he felt

00:05:47.190 --> 00:05:48.949
it in his soul.

00:05:48.949 --> 00:05:51.880
And as a six year old, when I was listening
to this melody --

00:05:51.880 --> 00:05:52.880
[plucks guitar string]

00:05:52.880 --> 00:06:00.449
I have an electric acoustic which is not plugged
in so if you can't hear the chords --

00:06:00.449 --> 00:06:01.990
[strums guitar]

00:06:01.990 --> 00:06:03.530
forgive me.

00:06:03.530 --> 00:06:04.530
[laughs]

00:06:04.530 --> 00:06:07.389
[playing guitar and humming]

00:06:07.389 --> 00:06:12.069
So Amir Khusro came up with this melody --

00:06:12.069 --> 00:06:18.650
[playing guitar and singing in foreign language]

00:06:18.650 --> 00:06:22.410
[playing guitar in background]

00:06:22.410 --> 00:06:26.169
And as he played--

00:06:26.169 --> 00:06:38.090
There was this pulse to it which goes like
this.

00:06:38.090 --> 00:06:44.729
[playing guitar and counting]

00:06:44.729 --> 00:06:58.000
One, two, three four. One, two, three, four.

00:06:58.000 --> 00:07:14.800
So he asked people who ever were coming together
to just connect with the pulse. And I'll ask

00:07:14.800 --> 00:07:15.849
you as well.

00:07:15.849 --> 00:07:16.849
Two, three, four.

00:07:16.849 --> 00:07:17.849
[playing guitar]

00:07:17.849 --> 00:07:18.849
Put your hands together.

00:07:18.849 --> 00:07:19.849
[sound of people clapping to music in background]

00:07:19.849 --> 00:07:20.849
[playing guitar and singing in foreign language]

00:07:20.849 --> 00:07:21.849
And as you just did, accelerated with the
beat as one.

00:07:21.849 --> 00:07:25.710
[playing guitar and people clapping to music
in background]

00:07:25.710 --> 00:07:31.289
[playing guitar and singing in foreign language;
tempo increasing]

00:07:31.289 --> 00:07:32.530
Your turn.

00:07:32.530 --> 00:07:37.479
[Salman Ahmad and audience singing in foreign
language]

00:07:37.479 --> 00:07:38.479
Everyone.

00:07:38.479 --> 00:07:43.060
[Salman Ahmad and audience singing in foreign
language]

00:07:43.060 --> 00:07:49.259
[Salman Ahmad clapping; audience clapping
and singing in foreign language]

00:07:49.259 --> 00:07:54.830
[Salman Ahmad singing in foreign language
and audience clapping]

00:07:54.830 --> 00:08:01.310
Keep it going.

00:08:01.310 --> 00:08:35.890
[Salman Ahmad singing and audience singing
and clapping]

00:08:35.890 --> 00:08:53.180
[audience clapping and singing]

00:08:53.180 --> 00:09:14.790
[Salman Ahmad singing with audience]

00:09:14.790 --> 00:10:02.340
[Salman Ahmad playing guitar and singing with
audience who is clapping]

00:10:02.340 --> 00:10:03.560
So that --

00:10:03.560 --> 00:10:05.820
[applause]

00:10:05.820 --> 00:10:12.400
Well, thank you for coming, coming along on
this experiment.

00:10:12.400 --> 00:10:22.380
But what music does is that complete strangers
facing each other can attune, synergize, and

00:10:22.380 --> 00:10:25.120
have empathy for each other.

00:10:25.120 --> 00:10:32.730
And I've now been -- I graduated from medical
school and I told my parents, "Give me one

00:10:32.730 --> 00:10:40.240
year to play music." But I didn't tell them
how many days in that one year. So they played

00:10:40.240 --> 00:10:48.231
along and then they realized it's not gonna
happen to be a Sharif doctor.

00:10:48.231 --> 00:10:50.580
[laughter]

00:10:50.580 --> 00:10:58.380
And on this journey, as I've felt about the
Qawwali, when I was 11 years old my family

00:10:58.380 --> 00:11:05.520
moved to the States, to New York. And for
the first two years I was there, I moved at

00:11:05.520 --> 00:11:13.390
the age of 11, first two years I was there,
my two best friends were TV and radio.

00:11:13.390 --> 00:11:19.020
And it seemed like, how do you make sense
of this culture which is so, so different

00:11:19.020 --> 00:11:26.390
from where you grew up? Until one day a kid
in school by the name of Danny Spitz, who

00:11:26.390 --> 00:11:34.600
went on to form the heavy metal band Anthrax,
he went to my high school. And he said, "Listen

00:11:34.600 --> 00:11:39.000
Sal, you need to do something. You have to
get cool."

00:11:39.000 --> 00:11:43.380
[laughter]

00:11:43.380 --> 00:11:51.200
And cool? So he said, "I have this ticket
in my back pocket." Danny was always, he was

00:11:51.200 --> 00:11:55.770
selling something, so he said, "I have this
ticket in my back pocket. You can have this

00:11:55.770 --> 00:12:03.320
red ticket. And it's for Monday night at a
show at Madison Square Garden and if you come

00:12:03.320 --> 00:12:07.660
to this show, you will become cool." It was
that simple.

00:12:07.660 --> 00:12:13.700
And now I'm thinking in my head while he's
putting this ticket, there is my mother, conservative

00:12:13.700 --> 00:12:18.930
Pakistani woman, sending me to a rock concert
in Madison Square Garden at the age of 13,

00:12:18.930 --> 00:12:21.580
is not gonna happen.

00:12:21.580 --> 00:12:29.080
But there was a whisper in my heart. Everybody
has a whisper in their heart, a passion, right?

00:12:29.080 --> 00:12:32.000
My whisper said, "Get the ticket."

00:12:32.000 --> 00:12:37.580
So I bought the ticket off of him and went
home and I told my mother that this rock concert

00:12:37.580 --> 00:12:41.980
is happening and the entire school is going
to --

00:12:41.980 --> 00:12:42.980
[laughter]

00:12:42.980 --> 00:12:46.290
to see this rock concert and there's only
one ticket for a Monday night and I bought

00:12:46.290 --> 00:12:47.680
this ticket.

00:12:47.680 --> 00:12:54.000
So my mother Shaheen -- she looked into my
eyes and she said, "If you do drugs, I will

00:12:54.000 --> 00:12:55.000
disown you."

00:12:55.000 --> 00:12:56.000
[laughter]

00:12:56.000 --> 00:12:57.290
[pause]

00:12:57.290 --> 00:13:02.670
Then she drove me to Madison Square Garden.
And I tell this story in my book, "Rock &amp; Roll

00:13:02.670 --> 00:13:08.980
Jihad" as well. And as I got off three blocks
away from Madison Square Garden, I walk on

00:13:08.980 --> 00:13:15.410
the pavement and I saw thousands and thousands
of kids long hair, torn jeans, peace signs,

00:13:15.410 --> 00:13:19.830
and an expression which said, "dazed and confused."

00:13:19.830 --> 00:13:26.030
And as I walked into the Garden it says, "Led
Zeppelin Live in Concert." And I didn't know

00:13:26.030 --> 00:13:30.480
what Led Zeppelin was. It could have been
the Bay City Rollers for all I was concerned.

00:13:30.480 --> 00:13:36.510
But what was interesting was this cultural,
this community because for the first hour

00:13:36.510 --> 00:13:41.420
there was no band out there, there was just
like these layers of smoke everywhere --

00:13:41.420 --> 00:13:43.020
[laughter]

00:13:43.020 --> 00:13:45.260
which smelled kind of funny as well.

00:13:45.260 --> 00:13:46.600
[laughter]

00:13:46.600 --> 00:13:54.090
And so I was like this, almost like watching
it as a scientist of what happens [chuckles]

00:13:54.090 --> 00:13:55.090
at a rock concert.

00:13:55.090 --> 00:14:03.170
So after waiting for about an hour the lights
go down and these four guys come up on stage.

00:14:03.170 --> 00:14:11.050
One of them has this two-headed guitar with
dragons painted on his pants and he starts

00:14:11.050 --> 00:14:12.050
playing something like this.

00:14:12.050 --> 00:14:23.790
[strumming guitar Led Zeppelin tune]

00:14:23.790 --> 00:14:29.950
And as he plays in, the drums come in and
the keyboards come in. All of a sudden everybody

00:14:29.950 --> 00:14:32.990
starts screaming, "Kashmir!"

00:14:32.990 --> 00:14:35.490
[laughter]

00:14:35.490 --> 00:14:37.990
[pause]

00:14:37.990 --> 00:14:40.160
Now if you come from South Asia --

00:14:40.160 --> 00:14:41.750
[laughter]

00:14:41.750 --> 00:14:45.140
you know that that is nothing to cheer about.
[laughs]

00:14:45.140 --> 00:14:46.860
[laughter]

00:14:46.860 --> 00:14:52.350
Yet, but for those three hours that I stood
in the 63rd row watching Led Zeppelin perform,

00:14:52.350 --> 00:14:55.010
it transformed me.

00:14:55.010 --> 00:14:59.450
Here was something, I was a complete cultural
outsider, didn't know what the songs were

00:14:59.450 --> 00:15:05.300
about, what the lyrics meant, but I just intuitively
understood; just the way I understood Qawwali

00:15:05.300 --> 00:15:13.830
music. That this is something very, this is
familiar, this is powerful.

00:15:13.830 --> 00:15:20.860
And so sound vibrations always stuck with
me as a teenager that sound vibrations are

00:15:20.860 --> 00:15:25.160
not to be dismissed lightly, that this is
yet entertainment.

00:15:25.160 --> 00:15:36.750
I've followed my path, the whisper I'm talking
to you about, there's a saying by the poet

00:15:36.750 --> 00:15:42.390
Muhammad Iqbal he said and I'll translate
into English, he said, "That whisper in your

00:15:42.390 --> 00:15:49.870
heart has strength. That whisper in your heart
has strength. It may not have wings but it

00:15:49.870 --> 00:15:55.230
has the power to fly." [Speaks in Hindi].
That whisper in your heart.

00:15:55.230 --> 00:16:01.670
And my whisper was saying that, "Yes, you're
stuck, you have all the reasons not to become

00:16:01.670 --> 00:16:05.360
a musician. You have all the reasons not to
follow your heart, you have all the reasons

00:16:05.360 --> 00:16:10.600
not to follow your passion, but this is who
you really are."

00:16:10.600 --> 00:16:16.080
And I think once you start listening to the
whisper, it becomes louder and louder and

00:16:16.080 --> 00:16:24.180
louder. And as I went through my career, and
my book is based on what I'm talking to you

00:16:24.180 --> 00:16:30.600
about, I understood also that when you see
with the heart, all the masks fall down. Music

00:16:30.600 --> 00:16:33.830
allows us to see with the heart.

00:16:33.830 --> 00:16:40.510
And recently in the last, all my life, social
service because I went to med school, my wife

00:16:40.510 --> 00:16:48.380
Samina who's here, is also a doctor. We understood
that social service, healing has to be part

00:16:48.380 --> 00:16:50.340
of whatever we do in our lives.

00:16:50.340 --> 00:16:56.560
So I've always tried to sort of balance arts
and culture and social service and our non-profit

00:16:56.560 --> 00:17:06.250
organization SSGWI. There's a website for
it as well SSGWI dot org, uses arts and culture

00:17:06.250 --> 00:17:14.709
to build dialog, to communicate and talk about
all kinds of things from India, Pakistan,

00:17:14.709 --> 00:17:19.600
conflict resolution to HIV and AIDS and I
wanted to, I hope we're not running over time.

00:17:19.600 --> 00:17:25.939
I just wanna show quickly two of the kind
of videos that using arts and culture we've

00:17:25.939 --> 00:17:26.939
done.

00:17:26.939 --> 00:17:35.000
The first is titled, Alvida. And it's about
a Pakistani woman who lives with HIV and AIDS,

00:17:35.000 --> 00:17:40.470
lost her husband. This is a true story. Lost
her husband and then found herself ostracized

00:17:40.470 --> 00:17:47.259
by a community in which there's great stigma,
there's great discrimination. And it was because

00:17:47.259 --> 00:17:51.831
she stood up, she listened to the whisper
in her heart and she realized, "If I run away,

00:17:51.831 --> 00:17:54.460
where can I run away?"

00:17:54.460 --> 00:18:01.460
And her story was so empowering, so powerful
that I did a video for that.

